(meaning ‘beetle, insect’) or Old English <i>wigga</i> ‘beetle, insect’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’."],"variants":[{"name":"Wignall","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Wiggenhall (Norfolk), Wiggenholt (Sussex), Wignal, a minor place near Holmes in the parish of Croston (Lancashire). The Norfolk placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wicga</i> (genitive <i>Wicgan</i>; see   Wigley  ) + Old English <i>halh</i> ‘nook, corner of land’. The Sussex placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wicga</i> (genitive <i>Wicgan</i>) + Old English <i>holt</i> ‘wood, thicket’. The Lancashire placename derives from the Old English personal name <i>Wicga</i> + Old English <i>h(e)alh</i> ‘nook, corner, recess’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Alice De Wigley was born in 1310 as the daughter of William De Wigley. She had at least 2 sons with Sir William Thomas Baldwin Baldewyne. She died in 1370, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1310–1370":"1310–1370","1301–1341":"1301–1341","1330–1354":"1330–1354","1330–1417":"1330–1417","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1301":"1301","1310":"1310","1354":"1354","1288":"12